---
/**
 * Keep inline tags on one line with outer spaces (Astro whitespace).
 * Never break before <em>/<strong>/<a> after a word.
 */
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Ricœur: Narrative Identity and the Dialectic of Selfhood | Foundations | Identity Engineering">
	<main class="min-h-screen">
		<section class="border-b border-white/10 px-6 pt-28 pb-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
				<a href="/foundations" class="mb-6 inline-block text-sm text-white/40 transition hover:text-white/70">
					← Foundations
				</a>
				<div class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Foundations · Ricœur</div>
				<h1 class="mt-3 text-5xl font-bold tracking-tighter leading-[0.95] text-white md:text-6xl">
					Narrative Identity and the Dialectic of Selfhood
				</h1>
				<p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-xl font-light leading-relaxed text-white/50">
					The hermeneutic view that the self is constituted through the stories we tell about ourselves — a dynamic narrative unity that holds together sameness (idem) and self-constancy (ipse) over time.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-12 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div class="rounded-2xl border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] p-5 text-base leading-relaxed text-white/60">
					<strong class="text-white/80">Reading protocol on this page:</strong> First Ricœur in his own terms. Then inspirations for Identity Engineering. Then additions from Identity Engineering perspective. The purpose here is not to describe Ricœur in his full being, but to distill the essential stance relevant to identity and learn from him within this framework. That is not a claim to devalue his work or to say it would be invalid when read on its own terms.
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">1 · Narrative Identity</div>
					<p>
						In <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Oneself as Another</em> (1990) Paul Ricœur develops a hermeneutic philosophy of the self. He argues that personal identity is fundamentally <strong class="text-white/80">narrative</strong>. We constitute ourselves as selves by telling stories about our lives — stories that connect past, present, and projected future into a meaningful whole.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						Narrative identity is not a static substance but a dynamic, interpretive achievement. It is through emplotment (the narrative ordering of events) that we achieve a form of unity and coherence over time.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">2 · The Dialectic of Idem and Ipse</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-white/10 bg-black/20 p-4 text-sm text-white/60">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Core distinction (Ricœur):</strong> Ricœur distinguishes between two poles of identity: <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">idem</em> (sameness) — the aspect of continuity and permanence over time — and <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">ipse</em> (selfhood) — the aspect of self-constancy through promises, commitments, and narrative fidelity to oneself.
					</div>
					<p>
						Idem corresponds to what analytic philosophers like Parfit critique (numerical sameness). Ipse is the ethical and narrative dimension: the capacity to keep one’s word, to remain faithful to one’s projects, and to maintain a coherent life story despite change.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						Narrative identity holds these two poles in tension and mediation. It allows us to say “I am the same person” in a meaningful, non-metaphysical way.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">3 · Relevance for Identity Engineering</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-400/20 bg-cyan-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Inspiration from Ricœur:</strong> identity is an active, interpretive, narrative achievement. We do not simply have an identity; we continuously construct and reconfigure it through storytelling and meaning-making.
					</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-violet-400/20 bg-violet-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">IE additions:</strong> narrative as a primary tool for maintaining and curving the Identity Stem; the idem-ipse dialectic as the tension between continuity and committed selfhood that geometric work must navigate; and narrative emplotment as a method for integrating past, present, and future projections into coherent, high-Mass identity geometry.
					</div>
					<ul class="space-y-4">
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Narrative as Stem-maintenance:</strong> Storytelling is one of the most powerful everyday practices for binding perceptions, memories, and intentions into a coherent Stem. Conscious narrative work (life review, future scripting, meaning-making) is a direct way to strengthen and curve identity geometry.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Idem vs. Ipse as geometric tension:</strong> The tension between sameness (continuity of the bundle) and self-constancy (committed projection) is a central dynamic that Identity Engineering must manage. High-Mass identity requires both stable connections and resolute forward projection.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Emplotment as curvature tool:</strong> Ricœur’s concept of emplotment (ordering events into a meaningful plot) is a hermeneutic analogue to geometric curvature. It allows us to reconfigure the meaning and direction of our identity trajectory.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">The capable self:</strong> Ricœur’s later emphasis on the “capable human being” (able to speak, act, narrate, and be responsible) aligns with the Architect level: the self that can consciously design and take responsibility for its own narrative geometry.
						</li>
					</ul>
					<p class="mt-6">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Differentiation:</strong> Ricœur brings a hermeneutic and narrative dimension that complements the analytic reductionism of Parfit and the ontological structures of Heidegger. While Parfit shows what identity reduces to, Ricœur shows how we actively achieve a livable unity through narrative practices. He bridges the analytic and continental traditions and connects back to Aristotle’s concept of emplotment and Heidegger’s temporality of Dasein. Narrative identity is the interpretive practice through which the geometric work of Identity Engineering becomes meaningful and sustainable over time.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 bg-white/[0.015] px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Sources</div>
					<ul class="space-y-2 text-base text-white/50">
						<li>
							Primary: Paul Ricœur, <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Oneself as Another</em> (1990), <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Time and Narrative</em> (1983–85).
						</li>
						<li>
							Overview: <a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/ricoeur/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy: Ricœur</a>.
						</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Related</div>
					<p>
						Ricœur is the major hermeneutic and narrative anchor. He completes the modern sequence by showing how identity is actively constituted through interpretive and narrative practices. This anchor brings the linguistic and meaning-making dimension into the Foundations series and demonstrates how narrative work serves as a primary tool for maintaining and reshaping identity geometry over time.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 px-6 py-14">
			<div class="mx-auto flex max-w-3xl flex-col gap-4 text-sm sm:flex-row sm:items-center sm:justify-between">
				<a href="/foundations" class="text-white/50 transition hover:text-white/80">← All foundations</a>
				<div class="flex flex-wrap gap-x-6 gap-y-2">
					<a href="/ontology" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Ontology</a>
					<a href="/blog" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Blog</a>
					<a href="/framework" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Framework</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>
	</main>
</Layout>
